Title : Patrick James McGlinchey
Text : Father '''Patrick James McGlinchey''' (6 June 1928<ref>''New York State, Passenger and Crew Lists, 1917-1967'' for Patrick J McGlinchey of St Columban's, Navan, Ireland</ref> â€“ 23 April 2018) was an Irish Catholic missionary from [[Raphoe]], [[County Donegal]]. He was credited with mobilizing international support and foreign volunteers to modernize livestock farming in [[South Korea]]. He arrived in [[Jeju Province|Jeju]], South Korea in 1954 under the auspices of the [[Missionary Society of St. Columban]], and established the St. Isidore Farm in 1961. His work with the latter earned him the nickname "pig priest".<ref name="KoreaTimesObituary">{{cite news|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/culture/2018/05/293_248124.html|last=Kang|first=Hyun-kyung|title=Irish priest, social entrepreneur McGlinchey dies|newspaper=The Korea Times|date=29 April 2018|access-date=11 June 2018}}</ref> He received the [[Ramon Magsaysay Award]] in 1975 and Ireland's [[Presidential Distinguished Service Award]] in 2014.<ref name="KoreaTimesObituary"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rmaward.asia/awardees/mcglinchey-patrick-james/|title=McGlinchey, Patrick James|publisher=Ramon Magsaysay Award Foundation|access-date=11 June 2018}}</ref> He died on 23 April 2018 at the age of 89 while undergoing treatment for [[myocardial infarction]] and [[kidney failure]].<ref name="KoreaTimesObituary"/> After his death, he was named an [[Honorary Citizen of South Korea]] in June 2018 in a ceremony attended by his nephew.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2018/06/05/0200000000AEN20180605010300315.html|title=Late Irish Catholic priest awarded honorary citizenship|agency=[[Yonhap]]|date=5 June 2018|access-date=11 June 2018}}</ref>

